data.content:
Your code **doesn't actually use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration changes**.

That said, for modern .NET you'd typically replace raw threads with `Task.Run` or `Parallel.ForEach`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is a modernization improvement, not a required migration fix. Your original code will compile and run as-is on .NET 8.
